article.description: Chamique Holdsclaw set a WNBA record with 24 rebounds to lead the Washington Mystics to a 74-70 season-opening win over the Charlotte Sting on Friday night.
article.headline: Holdsclaw sets WNBA record with 24 boards
article.linkText: Holdsclaw holds court with 24 rebounds in Mystics' win
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Chamique Holdsclaw set a WNBA record with
24 rebounds to lead the Washington Mystics to a 74-70
season-opening win over the Charlotte Sting on Friday night.

	   Holdsclaw also had 22 points as the Mystics spoiled the first
game for Charlotte under new owner Bob Johnson.

	   "I think they got her fired up by challenging her early on,''
Washington coach Marianne Stanley said of Holdsclaw. "After that
it was like, 'school is out.'''

	   The previous rebounding record was 21, held by four players. The
last to do it was Lisa Leslie of the Los Angeles Sparks, in a
victory over Orlando last July 22.

	   Johnson, the Washington billionaire who took over the Sting as
part of his $300 million deal to own Charlotte's NBA expansion
franchise, received a standing ovation from the crowd of 11,910
when he was introduced at midcourt just before the game.

	   "I told the Sting in our locker room, 'This is our first dance,
so let's give them something to talk about,''' Johnson said.

	   But with Johnson watching from a front-row seat at midcourt
between Charlotte Mayor Pat McCrory and WNBA commissioner Val
Ackerman, the Mystics jumped to a 32-19 lead, thanks to Holdsclaw's
dominance inside.

	   "Tonight I just fell in the flow rebounding, just going in
there being relentless,'' Holdsclaw said. "We're small, so we have
to use our quickness and get around people.''

	   The Sting cut the lead to two on Shalonda Enis' free throw with
29.8 seconds left to play. But on the next possession, Coco Miller
got behind the defense for a layup to seal it.

	   Stacey Dales Schuman finished with 20 points and eight assists
for Washington.

	   Allison Feaster scored 16 points for Charlotte, which shot 37
percent in Trudi Lacey's first game as coach.

	   "Chamique Holdsclaw is tough,'' Lacey said. "When they needed
offensive rebounds, they got them. We had a great crowd, a great
atmosphere, Bob was here, but we just flat-out didn't get it
done.''

	   The Sting's future had been in jeopardy after the NBA's Hornets
moved to New Orleans a year ago. Johnson has promised to promote
the Sting more and create a more fan-friendly atmosphere. Charlotte
had the second-worst attendance in the league last season.

	   The Sting players came out before the game with a NASCAR stock
car, Johnson's way of acknowledging the community's racing roots. A
new mascot, B.B. Sting, was introduced to replace Hugo the Hornet.

	   "This is the first time I've had the privilege of owning a
professional sports team and seeing it perform,'' Johnson said at
halftime. "We're going to do everything we can to aggressively
market the Sting.''
